Investigating the Potential Effects of the Elimination of NJ Transit Routes 24, 31, and 44

Final Project - Command Line GIS

Adam Caspari

For this project, we investigated which areas could potentially be affected by the discontinuation of the NJ Transit 24, 31, and 44 bus routes. These bus routes were served by a private bus operator until October 2023, when financial difficulties caused NJ Transit to assume control of the service. While NJ Transit has operated these routes consistently since that time, they have only agreed to do so on an interim basis. Since elimination of service on these routes is a realistic possibility, it is worthwhile to analyze what alternative services exist within these routes' service areas and to examine the characteristics of the areas where no viable alternatives would be available.

Data

Bus Stops

The primary dataset I used for this project was stop by line data obtained from the NJGIN Open Data site. The dataset included point data indicating the locations of all NJ Transit bus stops in the entire state of New Jersey. The routes served by each stop were specified in the dataset and any stop that served multiple routes was included once for each route. The data were prepared by the NJ Transit GIS Department and were downloaded as a CSV file with latitude and longitude coordinates. They were updated within the past month and had no data quality issues.

The bus stop data needed some processing before it was used to create network buffers (see below). This could be divided into three steps:

1.     I divided the stops between those used by the 24, 31, and 44 routes and those used by other routes.

2.     I limited the stops on other routes to only those within a one-mile buffer of the 24, 31, and 44 stops. I did this because stops outside of this buffer would be too far away to serve as viable alternatives to the 24, 31, and 44.

3.     I limited the stops on other routes to only those stops on routes that served Downtown Newark or Downtown Elizabeth. I did this because some bus stops that were in close proximity to 24, 31, and 44 stops were only served by routes that lacked service to the high-ridership destinations of Downtown Newark or Downtown Elizabeth. Since these downtown stops are critical destinations on the 24, 31, and 44, any route that lacked service to them would be a poor alternative to the 24, 31, and 44.

OpenStreetMap Network Data

I utilized OSMNx to obtain the OpenStreetMap walk network for all areas in Essex and Union Counties that were within 1 mile of the 24, 31, or 44 bus routes. I used the street network data exclusively to calculate network buffers. All network buffers showed the areas that could be reached within a ten minute walk of a starting point, assuming a walking speed of 4.5 mph. I calculated 3 separate network buffers in total:

1.     I calculated a network buffer around two central intersections in Downtown Newark (Broad Street and Market Street) and Downtown Elizabeth (Broad Street and Jersey Avenue). These network buffers were intended to help us identify other routes that serve Downtown Newark and Downtown Elizabth that could serve as potential alternatives to the 24, 31, and 44 routes (see above).

2.     I calculated a network buffer around all stops on the 24, 31, and 44 bus routes to determine which areas were within a 10-minute walk of these routes. Once all buffers were calculated, I used the dissolve geoprocessing method to combine the buffers into a single multipolygon representing all areas within walking distance of these three routes.

3.     I calculated a network buffer around all stops on other NJ Transit routes that serve Downtown Newark and Downtown Elizabeth. This network buffer allowed to determine which areas are within a 10-minute walk of these routes. Once all buffers were calculated, I used the dissolve geoprocessing method to combine the buffers into a single multipolygon representing all areas within walking distance of alternative routes.

Once all of the above was completed, I used the difference overlay method to "subtract" the buffer calculated in #3 from the buffer calculated in #2. The resulting polygon represented area currently served by the 24, 31, and 44 routes that are not in close proximity to another route with direct service to Downtown Newark or Downtown Elizabeth.

Census Data

I also used data from US Census Bureau Table P2. This table is based on data from the 2020 Decennial Census and gives information about the number of individuals in each racial and ethic group living within each census block group. These data were accessed programmatically using the Python Census API. There appeared to be no issues with the quality of these data, however they had to be joined to a spatial data layer to be mapped. The spatial data layer utilized was from the Census Bureau's TIGER data, which was available for direct download as a zip file on the Census Bureau's site. The data were updated for the 2020 US Census. This dataset has a known issue with including water area, which is not ideal for our purposes. I had hoped to get tract data from IPUMS, but I had trouble accessing the system. The data table (P2) and the spatial data were combined via a join based on a GEOID field shared by both datasets.

Rail Stations

I also utilized rail station data from the NJGIN Open Data site for mapping purposes only. The dataset included point data indicating the locations of all NJ Transit rail stations in New Jersey. The data were prepared by the NJ Transit GIS Department and were downloaded as a CSV file with latitude and longitude coordinates. They were updated within the past month and had no data quality issues.

 

Findings

Using GIS methods (see data section above for details), we determined the areas within a 10 minute walk of the 24, 31, and 44 routes as well as areas within a 10 minute walk of alternative routes. This is shown on the map below:

In the interactive map above, the layer shown in red displays areas within a 10 minute walk of the 24, 31, and 44 bus routes. Conversely, the layer shown in green shows the areas within a 10 minute walk of alternate bus routes that serve Downtown Newark or Downtown Elizabeth. Note that some areas within a 10 minute walk of the 24, 31, and 44 bus routes are also served by alternative routes (these appear in yellow when both layers are turned on) but others are not served by any alternative routes (these are still shown in red when both layers are turned on).

Let's consider the demographics of the areas currently served by the 24, 31, and 44 that would have no alternative service. Since boundaries of the unserved areas don't match the boundaries of our census block groups, we must assume that the proportion of population that will lose access to bus service in each block group is equal to the proportion of the block group area that will lose service. This in turn assumes that population is evenly distributed across all block groups (which is highly unlikely to be the case but is also unlikely to introduce large errors). Using these assumptions, we can estimate that approximately 88,600 people live within the area that could lose 24, 31, and 44 bus service without having any viable alternatives. This population is estimated to be approximately 92.3% nonwhite, meaning that a potential service change on the 24, 31, and 44 routes could have disproportionate impacts on minority communities. We also estimate that the population density in this area is 16,500 people per square mile, which makes this area far more densely populated than New Jersey as a whole.

Let's look at detailed maps of the areas that wouldn't have service when the 24, 31, and 44 routes are eliminated. First, let's look at the proportion of nonwhite residents:

NOTE: The nonwhite population map above shows no cross-hatching for unreliable values because all values are reliable.

On the map above, the percentage of nonwhite population in each block group is represented on a choropleth map with a blue color scheme. The map also shows areas that will lose access to bus routes inside of a thick black outline. The map indicates that nearly all areas in which service will be eliminated are at least 88% nonwhite.

Now, let's look at population density:

NOTE: The density map above shows no cross-hatching for unreliable values because all values are reliable.

On the map above, the population density of each block group in Essex and Union Counties is represented on a choropleth map with a red color scheme. This map also shows areas that will lose access to bus routes inside of a thick black outline. The map indicates that many areas in which bus service will become unavailable are among the densest in Essex and Union Counties.

Another important question when assessing the elimination of these routes is whether NJ Transit's rail system could serve any of the passengers displaced by the elimination of the 24, 31, or 44 bus routes. The map below shows the rail stations and the area that would lose bus service if the 24, 31, and 44 were eliminated:


As we can see, many (but not all) areas that would lose bus service would have rail stations nearby. All of these rail stations have direct rail service to Downtown Newark, so this could be a useful alternative if the 24, 31, and 44 were eliminated.
